## Auto-Invocation Rules

0. **Auto-Implement (Master)**: When the user provides **any** requirement (short sentence, standard format, or feature-sized request), invoke the `auto-implement` skill. It orchestrates the full pipeline: parse → implement → route → RBAC → test → lint → docs → verify. The user provides only the requirement; everything else is background work.

1. **Code Structure**: When implementing any requirement (new feature, page, component, API), read the `code-structure` skill first for placement and dependency rules; then add or update tests automatically (do not wait for the user to ask for tests).

2. **Test Generation**: When a new `.tsx` or `.ts` source file is created under `src/`, check if a colocated test file exists. If not, invoke the `test-generation` skill to create one. Exceptions: `types.ts`, `branded.ts`, `index.ts` (barrel), `<page>.contracts.ts`, `<page>.constants.ts`, `<page>.route.tsx`, `<page>.manifest.ts`, `<PAGE>.OVERVIEW.md`. Do not ask the user whether to add tests — generate them as part of the implementation.

2b. **E2E Test IDs**: When adding or changing interactive UI, or when the user wants Playwright-ready selectors, invoke the `e2e-testids` skill: apply naming conventions, add `data-testid` on pages/forms/nav, and update `docs/reference/e2e-testids-inventory.md`.

2c. **Playwright E2E**: When writing or refactoring `tests/e2e/*.e2e.test.ts`, invoke **`playwright-e2e`**: hybrid selectors (`data-testid` actions + `getByRole`/`getByLabel` guards) via `tests/utils/e2e-hybrid.ts`.

3. **Route island**: When creating or refactoring any route or sub-route, invoke `route-island` first: identical directory tree, `<PAGE>.OVERVIEW.md`, imports stay inside the island (+ core/shared/lib/stores only).

3b. **Routing & tenancy**: When adding or changing routes under `organization/$organizationSlug/`, root `/dashboard`, `routeTree.tsx` guards, `gatewayFromManifest`, session hydrate/invalidate, or settings hash behavior, invoke **`routing-tenancy`** after `route-island`. See **`agent-os/rules/routing-tenancy-sync.mdc`**.

3c. **Resource CRUD**: When scaffolding a backend resource (list + URL-driven create/edit dialogs, `*.resource.ts`, L7 bootstrap), invoke **`resource-crud`** after `route-island` (+ **`routing-tenancy`** when org-scoped).

3d. **HTTP / forms / errors**: When wiring form mutations to `apiClient`, mapping 422 to RHF, handling 429, or wrapping read panels in `QueryBoundary`, invoke **`http-forms-errors`** (with `composition-patterns` for form structure).

3e. **Platform hygiene**: When touching env schema, `platformConfig`, `build-env.ts`, knip, or platform validators, invoke **`platform-hygiene`** (env key add/rename/remove chains **`env-schema-add`** first). See **`agent-os/rules/platform-hygiene-sync.mdc`**.

4. **Page Scaffolding**: When creating a new page, invoke `page-scaffolding` (after `route-island`) to ensure all standard files are created and `data-testid` attributes are placed (via `e2e-testids` skill).

5. **Component Promotion**: When importing a page-specific component into a second page, invoke the `component-promotion` skill to move it to `shared/`.

6. **Code Quality**: When modifying `eslint.config.mjs`, `.husky/*`, or `.github/workflows/pr-ci.yml`, invoke the `code-quality-security` skill for consistency checks.

7. **Lint Guard**: After every implementation that adds or changes source files, invoke the `lint-guard` skill to fix all ESLint and TypeScript errors before responding. Do not announce this step — just ensure zero errors.

8. **Code Smells / Best Practices**: When any code is added or changed under `src/`, invoke the `code-smells-best-practices` skill on the **modified/live code only**. Check dependency rules (app not importing from pages), import formatting, no inline styles, no `any`, apiClient from fetch-client, form-error testid consistency. Fix issues in the same change set without asking.

9. **Requirement Format**: When the user's request is vague or feature-sized (e.g. "we need notifications", "add the billing feature") and they have **not** provided a requirement doc in the standard format (What, Where, Acceptance criteria), invoke the `requirement-format` skill: ask them to fill the template from `docs/getting-started/requirement-format.md` (or paste it) and point to `docs/getting-started/requirements/sample-requirement.md`. Full intake (types, skills, rules): **docs/getting-started/requirement-intake.md**. When they **do** provide a requirement in that format, parse it and implement fully (code-structure + page-scaffolding + tests + route + RBAC) without asking.

10. **Documentation Maintenance**: When adding a new doc, moving/renaming docs, or changing project structure that affects README/CLAUDE or doc links, invoke the `documentation-maintenance` skill to place the doc correctly and keep README, CLAUDE, and docs/README.md in sync.

11. **Extension/Settings Recommendations**: When the user asks about extensions, IDE setup, or productivity, invoke the `extension-settings-recommendations` skill. When adding or changing tooling that affects the IDE (new test framework, new linter, new language, new config file), consider invoking it to suggest or update workspace extensions and settings; apply updates if clearly beneficial and non-intrusive.

12. **Project Health Check**: When the user asks to "check everything", "run health check", "verify the project", "make sure everything works", or after a major code change involving 10+ files, invoke the `project-health-check` skill to audit docs, tests, lint, build, and bundle.

13. **Full Code Review**: When the user asks to "run code review", "generate code review report", "full code review", or "code review report", invoke the `full-code-review` skill. Run `pnpm report:code-review` to generate the report; the skill guides the AI when the user wants the AI to produce it.

14. **shadcn/ui (single skill)**: For **any** shadcn/ui work — building, adding, fixing, debugging, styling, composing, running the CLI, touching `components.json`/presets, **and choosing which component/block to use** — read **`agent-os/skills/shadcn/SKILL.md`** first and follow its workflow + Critical Rules + its **"Project rules — core-fe"** section (allowed 20 sources + selection flow). This is now the **one canonical shadcn skill** (the former `shadcn-component-selection` is merged into it). Use the project runner (`pnpm dlx shadcn@latest …`); check installed components and `search`/`docs` before writing custom markup. Enforce semantic tokens, `gap-*` not `space-*`, `size-*` for equal w/h, `cn()`, `data-icon` on button icons, full Card/Tabs/Avatar composition. Do not announce reading it — just follow it.

15. **frontend-design (installed skill)**: When **building, styling, or beautifying any UI** (page, component, layout, interface), read **`agent-os/skills/frontend-design/SKILL.md`** for design-thinking and aesthetic quality (typography hierarchy, color/theme intent, motion on high-impact moments, spatial composition, depth/atmosphere, memorable details — avoid generic "AI slop"). **Apply it *within* this project's guardrails — those take precedence:** components come from shadcn via `agent-os/skills/shadcn/SKILL.md` + the 20 allowed sources (`agent-os/rules/ui-sources.mdc`); colors use the neutral semantic tokens in `src/index.css` (no raw colors, no purple-on-white); fonts and brand stay as configured unless the user asks to change them; accessibility/UX follows `web-design-guidelines`. Use `frontend-design` to elevate craft and polish, **not** to override the component library, design tokens, or brand. For ad-hoc standalone artifacts the user may grant more creative latitude.

16. **find-skills (installed skill)**: When the user asks "is there a skill for X", wants to discover/install new capabilities, or a task has **no matching skill in this router or skill-registry**, read **`agent-os/skills/find-skills/SKILL.md`** and use the Skills CLI (`npx skills find <query>`, `npx skills add <owner/repo@skill>`). Prefer reputable, high-install skills; present options before installing. Install into `agent-os/skills/` (tracked in `skills-lock.json`), then **wire the new skill into this router, `skill-registry`, and docs** (as done for `shadcn`, `frontend-design`, `find-skills`).

17. **ui-ux-pro-max (installed skill)**: A searchable design-intelligence DB (50+ styles, 161 palettes, 57 font pairings, 161 product types, 99 UX guidelines, charts, and per-stack rules incl. shadcn). When making design decisions or reviewing UI, **query it for guidance** via Python: `python3 agent-os/skills/ui-ux-pro-max/scripts/search.py "<query>" --domain <style|color|ux|typography|chart|product|icons> [--stack shadcn]` (requires `python3`; scripts are local-only — BM25 over bundled CSVs, no network). Use its `--stack shadcn` and `ux` guidance most. **Project guardrails win:** do **not** apply its palette/font/style suggestions in a way that overrides our neutral semantic tokens (`src/index.css`), configured fonts/brand, or shadcn component choices — treat it as advisory; the authoritative skills remain `shadcn` (components/tokens), `frontend-design` (craft), and `web-design-guidelines` (a11y). Don't run `--persist` (writes `design-system/` files) unless the user asks.

18. **i18n-constants**: When extracting inline strings, test ids, analytics events, or defaults into `<page>.constants.ts` + locale JSON, or when adding user-facing copy to a route island, read **`agent-os/skills/i18n-constants/SKILL.md`**. One island or module per change; wire react-i18next namespace; manifest `testId` imports from constants.

18b. **env-schema-add**: When adding, renaming, or removing env vars (`env-schema.ts`, `.env.example`), read **`agent-os/skills/env-schema-add/SKILL.md`**. Run `pnpm tool:sync-env-example`; follow **`agent-os/rules/env-schema-add-sync.mdc`**.

19. **theme-axis-audit (mandatory for axis work)**: When the user asks to audit/fix Appearance or Shuffle axes, continue **"one by one"**, or name a specific axis (`elevation`, `density`, …), read **`agent-os/skills/theme-axis-audit/SKILL.md`** + **`docs/reference/theme-axis-audit-playbook.md`**. Complete Phases 0–4 in one cycle, deliver the detailed report, update the playbook status tracker. See **`agent-os/rules/theme-axis-audit.mdc`**.

19b. **Preset product-design rules**: When changing **`presets.ts`**, Appearance pickers, `applyGeneratedTheme`, default axes, or dense product UI under Shuffle, read **`docs/reference/preset-product-design-rules.md`** and follow **`agent-os/rules/preset-product-design.mdc`** (typography floor 12px, density≠font size, touch targets, no opacity page fades).

19c. **PWA manifest sync**: When changing **`app-manifest.ts`**, **`manifest.webmanifest`**, **`app-icon.svg`**, PWA PNGs, favicon, or install **`theme_color`**, read **`agent-os/skills/pwa-manifest/SKILL.md`** + **`docs/reference/pwa-manifest-and-app-icon.md`**. Edit `app-manifest.ts` first; sync JSON, `index.html`, `page-head.ts`, and PNGs; run **`app-manifest.test.ts`**. See **`agent-os/rules/pwa-manifest-sync.mdc`**.

19d. **Local production perf**: When measuring bundle size or Lighthouse, **`pnpm build`** then **`pnpm preview`** (or static `serve dist`) — never Lighthouse on **`pnpm dev`**. See **`docs/reference/local-production-perf.md`**.

20. **UI & craft stack (precedence — no conflicting taste skills):**
    - **Default** (any UI build/style): **`shadcn`** → **`frontend-design`** → **`web-design-guidelines`**. Query **`ui-ux-pro-max`** for advisory UX/style/chart hints only; never override semantic tokens (`src/index.css`), Lucide icons, or shadcn choices.
    - **Full redesign / audit / “impeccable”** (user explicitly asks): add **`impeccable`** after `shadcn`, still within project guardrails (`ui-sources.mdc`, tokens, route-island).
    - **Motion implementation:** **`animejs`** (this repo’s animation library). Read **`emil-design-eng`** for when/why motion; **`review-animations`** for PR review of motion code only.
    - **Removed / do not invoke:** `high-end-visual-design`, `redesign-existing-projects`, `shadcn-ui-blocks`, `image-to-code`, `motion-framer`, `full-output-enforcement` — they conflict with core-fe guardrails or duplicate `shadcn` / `frontend-design`.

## Orchestration manifests (machine-readable cross-refs)

The routes above are the human-readable map; the same relationships are declared
as data for tooling and the eval gates:

- **Skill chains** — `agent-os/skills/chains.json`: named, ordered sequences for
  multi-skill work (`page-change`, `component-promotion`, `resource-crud`,
  `ui-review`, `form-mutation`, `data-hook`, `styling`, `env-change`). Each
  `trigger` mirrors a row in `agent-os/docs/skill-triggers.md`.
- **Skill groups** — `agent-os/skills/groups.json`: every skill in exactly one
  group (ui-design, routing-pages, testing, quality, docs, i18n, platform,
  workflow, external).
- **Review pipelines** — `agent-os/agents/pipelines.json`: read-only reviewer
  agents run by `/pre-merge-review` (`verifier` → `docs-auditor`) and
  `/prod-readiness` (`dependency-auditor` → `bundle-size-reviewer`); each
  finding hands off to the skill that fixes it. Catalog:
  `agent-os/docs/agents-catalog.md`.
- **File-pattern routing** — `agent-os/docs/skill-triggers.md` is the source for
  "which skill(s) when file X changes"; add a row (and a `triggers.json` case)
  when wiring a new route.

`agent-os/evals/check.ts` asserts every chain step, group member, pipeline step,
and handoff resolves to a real skill/agent, so these manifests cannot drift.

If multiple skills match, read the most specific one first.
